                          Labor Market Information

   Federal Information Sources
   Below are links to federal sites. These sites provide labor market,
   economic and demographic data for the United States. Other links to
   federal agencies can be found at the Library of Congress.

   FirstGov  (www.firstgov.gov), Your First Click to the U.S. Government
       Department of Agriculture  (www.usda.gov)
       Department of Commerce  (www.doc.gov)

        Bureau of Economic Analysis  (www.bea.doc.gov)
                Economic statistics, including per capita income, and the
                "Survey of Current Business".

        Bureau of the Census  (www.census.gov)
                A general purpose statistical agency that collects,
                tabulates, and publishes a wide variety of demographic and
                economic data.

        Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO)  (www.uspto.gov)
                Examines applications for and issues patents and
                trademarks.

   Department of Labor  (www.dol.gov)

        Bureau of Labor Statistics  (www.bls.gov)
                Principal fact-finding agency for the Federal government
                in the broad field of labor economics and statistics.

        Occupational Health and Safety Administration
                (OSHA)  (www.osha.gov)
                Develops and monitors occupational safety and health
                standards.

   Independent Agencies:

        Environmental Protection Agency  (www.epa.gov)
                Formulates and implements actions that lead to a balance
                between human activities and the ability of natural
                systems to support life.

        Federal Trade Commission  (www.ftc.gov)
                Enforces federal antitrust and consumer protection laws.

        Securities & Exchange Commission  (www.sec.gov)
                Responsible for administering the federal security laws to
                protect investors in securities markets.

        Small Business Administration  (www.sbaonline.sba.gov)
                Aids, counsels, assists, and protects the interests of
                small business; makes loans to small business concerns.

